w, Ireland":"St Mullin's, County Carlow, Ireland","Leinster, Ireland":"Leinster, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Art","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Arthur .  There is also a traditional Gaelic name of this form (from <i>art</i> ‘bear’ ) which has generally been Anglicized as <i>Arthur</i>, although it in fact has no connection with that name. In the diminutive form <i>Artan</i> it has given rise to the Skye surname <i>Mac Artain</i>, Anglicized as <i>McCartan</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mór","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Art Mór MacMurrough-Kavanagh King of Leinster was born in 1357, in Ireland, his father, Art Mór Mac Murchadha Caomhánachh King of Leinster, was 53 and his mother, Mrs Art Mor Kavanagh Art Mor Mac Murchadha Caomhanachh, was 53. He married Lady Elizabeth Calf le Veel of Norragh in 1390. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1417, in Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland, at the age of 60, and was buried in St Mullin's, County Carlow, Ireland."},"et":{"1357–1417":"1357–1417","1350–1361":"1350–1361","1356–1402":"1356–1402","1365–1445":"1365–1445","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1385–1478":"1385–1478","–1417":"–1417","–Male":"Surnud","1305–1377":"1305–1377","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1385":"1385","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1390":"1390","from 1375 to 1417":"1375 kuni 1417","1305":"1305","1402":"1402","1357":"1357","1478":"1478","1445":"1445","1356":"1356","1377":"1377","1431":"1431","1365":"1365","about 1348":"umbes 1348","1417":"1417","Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland":"Ferns, County Wex